    <h2>How to Actually Use This Plan</h2>

    <p>This is a framework, not a script. The plan isn't meant to be followed rigidly day-by-day — the days are interchangeable. What matters is hitting 30g at breakfast, 30–35g at lunch, 35g at dinner, and closing the gap with a snack if you're short.</p>

    <div class="tips-box">
      <h3>Four Things That Make This Work</h3>
      <p style="font-size:0.92rem; color:var(--muted); margin-bottom:0.85rem;">If you only do these four things, this plan works.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Keep rotisserie chicken on hand.</strong> It's the fastest 35g of protein in any grocery store. Buy one Sunday, eat from it for three days.</li>
        <li><strong>Stock cottage cheese and Greek yogurt every week.</strong> These two foods alone can save a breakfast or a snack at any moment. They require zero prep.</li>
        <li><strong>Keep canned tuna and salmon in the pantry.</strong> A can of tuna is 25–27g with no cooking, no refrigeration until opened, and takes 90 seconds to prepare.</li>
        <li><strong>Track the number, not the meal.</strong> You don't need to log every ingredient. Log the protein grams. One number. That's the habit that sticks.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <p>The 80/20 rule applies here: <strong>most men over 50 eat the same 8–12 foods in rotation</strong>. You're probably already eating eggs, chicken, and ground beef. The meal plan above isn't asking you to learn new foods — it's asking you to structure what you already eat around a number that actually moves the needle.</p>

